[[File:Akademie der Wissenschaften und Literatur Mainz-3516.jpg|thumb|right]]
The '''Academy of Sciences and Literature''' ({{lang-de|Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur Mainz, AdW Mainz}}) is a [[Academy of Sciences|scientific academy]] in [[Mainz]], [[Germany]]. It was established in 1949 on an initiative of [[Alfred Döblin]].<ref name="about">{{cite web |url=http://www.adwmainz.de/die-akademie.html |title=Die Akademie |language=German |publisher=Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur |accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> The Academy is an affiliation of personalities from science, literature and music.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=2018 |title=adw-mainz |url=https://www.akademienunion.de/en/adw-mainz/ |work=Union of the German Academies of Sciences and Humanities |location=Berlin |access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref> The Academy’s goal is to support science and literature, and in doing so to help preserve and promote culture. It is divided in three classes: mathematics and natural sciences, humanities and social sciences, literature and music. Each class has up to 50 full and 50 corresponding members. It actively promotes interdisciplinary discourse, facilitates research projects and organizes a variety of public events. Notable members have been [[Niels Bohr]], [[Otto Hahn]], [[Konrad Lorenz]], [[Halldór Laxness]], [[Heinrich Böll]], und [[Jean-Marie Lehn]].<ref name="about" />

